                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/10149: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Tangier</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Childs</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tangier</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-21T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 21, 1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>107. I was informed by Meyrier, the principal assistant to Noguès in Rabat, that
                    Hitler had said privately recently the following in substance: “I know what is
                    going on in French North Africa. That does not disturb me. I know precisely how
                    many tanks and planes the French have there and I can crush in 3 days any
                    movement that raises its head there.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Childs</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
